{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622863"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:06:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:06:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16824"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16824"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.41,0.23,0.05,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76650"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9515"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62147"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8506"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22479"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76650"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spinal cord demonstrates characteristic structural variations at different vertebral levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the regional variation in spinal cord organisation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Grey matter decreases from rostral to caudal segments","Increased grey matter occurs in lumbar enlargement","White matter predominates in sacral segments","Lateral horns extend throughout all segments","Grey matter predominates in cervical segments"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased grey matter occurs in lumbar enlargement\u003C/strong\u003E is correct, as this region contains more motor neurones to innervate the lower limbs. Similarly, the cervical enlargement also has increased grey matter for upper limb innervation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrey matter decreases from rostral to caudal segments\u003C/strong\u003E - Grey matter actually increases at both cervical and lumbar enlargements\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhite matter predominates in sacral segments\u003C/strong\u003E - The sacral region has relatively less white matter as fewer tracts extend to this level\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral horns extend throughout all segments\u003C/strong\u003E - Lateral horns containing sympathetic preganglionic neurones are specifically present only in thoracic and upper lumbar segments\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrey matter predominates in cervical segments\u003C/strong\u003E - While cervical regions have grey matter enlargements, they actually contain proportionally more white matter due to ascending and descending tracts\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe regional variations in spinal cord structure reflect the functional requirements of different segments, with enlargements corresponding to limb innervation and autonomic functions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The lumbar and cervical enlargements of the spinal cord contain increased grey matter to supply innervation to the limbs.","White matter proportionally increases in rostral segments of the spinal cord due to ascending and descending tracts.","Lateral horns containing preganglionic autonomic neurones are present in thoracic and upper lumbar segments."],"references":["Harrow-Mortelliti M, Reddy V, Jimsheleishvili G. Physiology, Spinal Cord. 2023 Mar 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334987.","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62147"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16824"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62147"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T20:14:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T20:15:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9515"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76650"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"